**Think of airport security scanning your bag.**

- **Before pattern matching (old Java):** the scanner has to (1) test what's in the bag with instanceof — 'is this a laptop?' — then (2) tell the guard to open the bag and pull out the laptop with an explicit cast — 'yes, this is a Laptop; now unpack the laptop.' Two steps: test, then cast. Every single time.

```java
if (item instanceof Laptop) {
  Laptop laptop = (Laptop) item;    // redundant cast — we JUST tested it!
  scan(laptop.getSerial());
}
```

- **With pattern matching:** the scanner combines test + unpack. 'Is this a Laptop? If so, hand me the laptop as `laptop`.' One step.

```java
if (item instanceof Laptop laptop) {   // test AND bind
  scan(laptop.getSerial());
}
```

**And with record deconstruction (Java 21):** 'Is this a Laptop? If so, hand me its serial and its owner.' The scanner reaches inside and pulls out the parts you asked for:

```java
if (item instanceof Laptop(String serial, String owner)) {
  scan(serial);
}
```

Pattern matching lets you write **what you're looking for** instead of **the mechanics of finding it**.

sections.code:
// BEFORE (traditional Java) — instanceof-and-cast
Object o = ...;
if (o instanceof String) {
  String s = (String) o;              // manual, error-prone
  System.out.println(s.length());
} else if (o instanceof Integer) {
  Integer i = (Integer) o;
  System.out.println(i * 2);
} else if (o instanceof List) {
  List<?> list = (List<?>) o;         // unchecked cast, warnings
  System.out.println(list.size());
}

// AFTER (Java 21+) — pattern-matching switch
String result = switch (o) {
  case String s        -> "str length " + s.length();
  case Integer i       -> "int doubled " + (i * 2);
  case List<?> list    -> "list size " + list.size();
  case null            -> "was null";
  default              -> "unknown";
};

// File: PatternMatchingDemo.java  (Java 21+)
// Run: javac PatternMatchingDemo.java && java PatternMatchingDemo

public class PatternMatchingDemo {

  sealed interface Shape permits Circle, Square, Triangle {}
  record Circle(double r) implements Shape {}
  record Square(double side) implements Shape {}
  record Triangle(double base, double height) implements Shape {}

  // 1. instanceof pattern — test AND bind in one step
  static void describe1(Object o) {
    if (o instanceof String s && !s.isBlank()) {
      System.out.println("non-blank string len=" + s.length());
    } else if (o instanceof Integer i) {
      System.out.println("integer=" + i);
    } else {
      System.out.println("other");
    }
  }

  // 2. Pattern-matching switch with record deconstruction
  static double area(Shape s) {
    return switch (s) {
      case Circle(double r)                -> Math.PI * r * r;
      case Square(double side)             -> side * side;
      case Triangle(double b, double h)    -> 0.5 * b * h;
      // NO default — the compiler proves the switch is exhaustive over Shape
    };
  }

  // 3. Guarded pattern — refine a case with a when-clause
  static String category(Shape s) {
    return switch (s) {
      case Circle c when c.r() > 10   -> "big circle";
      case Circle c                    -> "small circle";
      case Square sq when sq.side() > 10 -> "big square";
      case Square sq                   -> "small square";
      case Triangle t                  -> "triangle base=" + t.base();
    };
  }

  // 4. Null-safe switch
  static String describe2(Object o) {
    return switch (o) {
      case null           -> "was null";     // explicit null case
      case String s       -> "string: " + s;
      case Integer i      -> "int: " + i;
      default             -> "other: " + o.getClass().getSimpleName();
    };
  }

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    describe1("hello");
    describe1(42);
    describe1(3.14);

    Shape[] shapes = { new Circle(2), new Circle(15), new Square(3), new Triangle(4, 5) };
    for (Shape sh : shapes) {
      System.out.printf("%-15s area=%.2f%n", category(sh), area(sh));
    }

    System.out.println(describe2(null));
    System.out.println(describe2("hi"));
    System.out.println(describe2(99));
  }
}

// Output:
//   non-blank string len=5
//   integer=42
//   other
//   small circle    area=12.57
//   big circle      area=706.86
//   small square    area=9.00
//   triangle base=4.0 area=10.00
//   was null
//   string: hi
//   int: 99

